                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Chicago&#44; July 16. 1894.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. S. Morais&#44; Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>These lines will be handed to you by a Mr. Bernard E.<lb/> Wolpert&#44;&#45;&#45;a young man who was born and raised in<lb/> some Russian town&#44; but who&#44; with his parents&#44; came to<lb/> America about 2 1<lb/>2 years ago.  Mr. Wolpert tells me that<lb/> he devoted his younger years&#44; while still in his native country&#44;<lb/> to talmudical studies&#44; and that&#44; besides other parts of the<lb/> Talmud&#44; he read and digested all of &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  He<lb/> also claims to be sufficiently advanced in English studies&#44; &#38;c.&#44;<lb/> so as to be able to enter into one of our American High Schools.<lb/></p>
            <p>Upon Mr. W.&#39;s urgent request&#44; I beg the liberty of<lb/> introducing him to you and to ask for him your kind<lb/> consideration.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours very respectfully<lb/>
                B. Felsenthal.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
